        "arguments": "{\"path\":\".claude/rules/docs/core-application.md\",\"content\":\"# Guanine(CodeEdit) — Core Application Documentation\\n> Auto-generated by Spark. Last updated: 2026-04-06\\n> Source area: core-application\\n\\n## Purpose\\nMonolithic Flask application (`file_merger.py`, ~2861 lines) implementing a multi-source file recovery and merge tool. Scans multiple source directories (including Windsurf/VS Code/Cursor editor history), detects conflicts via SHA-256 hashing and content normalization, provides interactive diff/merge editing, and copies resolved files to a target directory. Persistence uses per-session SQLite databases with WAL mode.\\n\\n## Data Flows\\n- **Configuration input:** User submits source directories, target directory, and ignore patterns via `/setup` POST → stored in `state` dict and persisted to SQLite via `save_config()`.\\n- **File scanning:** `FileScanner.build_inventory()` walks source directories in parallel (`ThreadPoolExecutor`, 8 workers) → emits progress events via `queue.Queue` → consumed by `/scan-events` SSE endpoint → results stored in `state['inventory']` and bulk-saved to SQLite via `save_inventory_state()`.\\n- **Conflict resolution:** User selects versions via `/resolve` POST or `/api/save-merge` POST → single-row UPDATE on `merge_items` table via `save_item_resolution()`.\\n- **Merge execution:** `MergeEngine.execute_merge()` copies selected file versions to target directory → progress via queue → `/merge-events` SSE → merge log saved as JSON file.\\n- **Editor history extraction:** `EditorHistoryExtractor.extract_all()` parses `entries.json` from editor history dirs → copies files with original paths to destination → progress via `/extract-events` SSE.\\n\\n## Invariants Enforced\\n- **Auto-categorization:** Files with a single version → `auto_unique`; multiple versions with identical SHA-256 → `auto_identical`; differing content → `conflict`.\\n- **Content normalization:** Files with identical content after line-ending and trailing-whitespace normalization are auto-resolved as `auto_identical` (even if SHA-256 differs).\\n- **Conflict default selection:** Unresolved conflicts default to the version with the most lines (fallback: largest file size for binary files).\\n- **Thread-local SQLite:** Each thread gets its own `sqlite3.Connection` via `threading.local()` — connections never cross thread boundaries.\\n- **WAL mode:** All SQLite databases use `PRAGMA journal_mode=WAL` for concurrent read access during background writes.\\n- **Legacy migration:** On startup, JSON flat files (`.merger_config.json`, `.merger_state.json`) are automatically migrated to the `sessions/` SQLite structure.\\n\\n## Definitions\\n\\n### Data Models\\n| Name | File | Description |\\n|------|------|-------------|\\n| `FileVersion` | `file_merger.py` | Dataclass: source metadata for a single file version (source_name, sha256, line_count, is_binary, timestamps). Includes `to_dict()` for serialization. |\\n| `MergeItem` | `file_merger.py` | Dataclass: groups multiple `FileVersion`s by relative path. Tracks category (auto_unique/auto_identical/conflict), selected_index, and resolved state. |\\n| `SourceConfig` | `file_merger.py` | Dataclass: source directory configuration (name, path, priority). |\\n\\n### Classes\\n| Class | File | Description |\\n|-------|------|-------------|\\n| `FileScanner` | `file_merger.py` | Scans source directories, computes hashes, detects binary files, auto-detects editor history dirs, builds merged inventory with categorization. |\\n| `MergeEngine` | `file_merger.py` | Generates unified diffs, executes file copy merges to target directory, maintains merge log. |\\n| `EditorHistoryExtractor` | `file_merger.py` | Discovers and extracts files from Windsurf/VS Code/Cursor local history directories by parsing `entries.json`. |\\n| `RecoveryAdvisor` | `file_merger.py` | Static suggestions for file recovery methods (git reflog, shadow copies, recycle bin, etc.). |\\n\\n### Key Functions\\n| Function | File | Description |\\n|----------|------|-------------|\\n| `generate_side_by_side_diff(version_a, version_b, context_lines)` | `file_merger.py` | Returns list of `{type, left_num, left_line, right_num, right_line}` dicts for git-merge-style rendering. |\\n| `_generate_merge_hunks(version_a, version_b)` | `file_merger.py` | Returns `{type, lines_a, lines_b, start_a, start_b}` hunks for interactive merge editor. |\\n| `_get_db(session_id)` | `file_merger.py` | Thread-local SQLite connection factory with WAL mode and 8MB cache. |\\n| `save_inventory_state(inventory)` | `file_merger.py` | Bulk INSERT of all merge_items and file_versions (transactional). |\\n| `save_item_resolution(relative_path, selected_index, resolved)` | `file_merger.py` | Single-row UPDATE on merge_items (instant, used during conflict resolution). |\\n| `save_batch_resolutions(updates)` | `file_merger.py` | Batch UPDATE via `executemany` for bulk resolve operations. |\\n| `load_inventory_state(session_id)` | `file_merger.py` | Loads inventory from SQLite, falls back to legacy JSON with automatic migration. |\\n| `_restore_session()` | `file_merger.py` | Called at module load; restores active session from SQLite or migrates legacy files. |\\n| `_compute_stats(inventory)` | `file_merger.py` | Returns `{total, auto_unique, auto_identical, conflicts, resolved, auto_merge}`. |\\n\\n### Flask Routes (Page endpoints)\\n| Route | Methods | Template | Description |\\n|-------|---------|----------|-------------|\\n| `/setup` | GET, POST | `setup.html` | Configuration form and scan initiation. |\\n| `/scan-progress` | GET | `scan_progress.html` | Scan progress page (SSE consumer). |\\n| `/inventory` | GET | `inventory.html` | File inventory with filtering, sorting, pagination. |\\n| `/conflicts` | GET | `conflicts.html` | Conflict listing page. |\\n| `/conflict/<path:filepath>` | GET | `conflict_detail.html` | Side-by-side diff and version selection for a conflict. |\\n| `/merge/<path:filepath>` | GET | `merge_editor.html` | Interactive line-by-line merge editor. |\\n| `/browse` | GET | `browse.html` | Split-pane file browser (data via API). |\\n| `/coverage` | GET | `coverage.html` | Per-source coverage dashboard. |\\n| `/log` | GET | `log.html` | Merge log and recovery suggestions. |\\n| `/extract-history` | GET, POST | `extract_history.html` | Editor history extraction form. |\\n| `/extract-progress` | GET | `extract_progress.html` | Extraction progress page (SSE consumer). |\\n\\n### Flask Routes (API/SSE endpoints)\\n| Route | Methods | Description |\\n|-------|---------|-------------|\\n| `/scan-events` | GET | SSE stream for scan progress. |\\n| `/merge-events` | GET | SSE stream for merge progress. |\\n| `/extract-events` | GET | SSE stream for extraction progress. |\\n| `/api/browse-tree` | GET | JSON: nested directory tree of inventory. |\\n| `/api/file-detail/<path:filepath>` | GET | HTML fragment: file detail panel with versions and diff. |\\n| `/api/file-content/<path:filepath>` | GET | JSON: raw file content for a specific version. |\\n| `/api/save-merge` | POST | JSON: save manually merged file content. |\\n| `/api/coverage` | GET | JSON: per-source coverage stats. |\\n| `/api/coverage-files/<source_name>` | GET | JSON: files belonging to a source, grouped by category. |\\n| `/resolve` | POST | Resolve single conflict (form submit). |\\n| `/resolve-toggle` | POST | Toggle resolved state (JSON API). |\\n| `/resolve-accept-defaults` | POST | Accept auto-selected versions for unresolved conflicts. |\\n| `/resolve-all-latest` | POST | Auto-resolve all conflicts by selecting latest version. |\\n| `/execute` | POST | Execute merge (form submit, runs in background). |\\n| `/export-log` | GET | Download merge log as JSON. |\\n| `/session/switch/<session_id>` | GET | Switch active session. |\\n| `/session/new` | GET | Create new empty session. |\\n| `/session/delete/<session_id>` | GET | Delete a session. |\\n\\n### Constants\\n| Name | File | Description |\\n|------|------|-------------|\\n| `DEFAULT_IGNORE` | `file_merger.py` | Set of directory/file patterns to skip during scan (`.git`, `node_modules`, `__pycache__`, etc.). |\\n| `BINARY_EXTENSIONS` | `file_merger.py` | Set of file extensions treated as binary. |\\n| `SESSIONS_DIR` | `file_merger.py` | Path to `sessions/` directory for SQLite databases. |\\n| `state` | `file_merger.py` | Global dict holding in-memory application state (sources, inventory, scanner, engine, status flags). |\\n| `app` | `file_merger.py` | Flask application instance. |\\n\\n## Module Dependencies\\n\\n### This area depends on:\\n| Area/Module | What is used | How |\\n|-------------|-------------|-----|\\n| Flask (external) | `Flask`, `render_template`, `request`, `redirect`, `url_for`, `jsonify`, `Response`, `stream_with_context`, `flash` | Web framework for all routes and template rendering |\\n| markupsafe (external) | `Markup` | Safe HTML rendering in templates |\\n| Python stdlib | `os`, `sys`, `hashlib`, `json`, `difflib`, `threading`, `fnmatch`, `shutil`, `time`, `queue`, `re`, `sqlite3`, `datetime`, `pathlib`, `dataclasses`, `typing`, `urllib.parse`, `concurrent.futures` | Core functionality |\\n| web-templates | 13 Jinja2 templates (`setup.html`, `inventory.html`, `conflicts.html`, etc.) | Rendered via `render_template()` in all page routes |\\n| project-root-and-scripts | `sessions/` directory | SQLite databases written to `sessions/<id>/session.db` |\\n\\n### Other areas depend on this:\\n| Area/Module | What they use | How |\\n|-------------|--------------|-----|\\n| web-templates | All Flask route endpoints and SSE streams | Templates consume `/api/*`, `/scan-events`, `/merge-events`, `/extract-events`, and page routes |\\n| project-root-and-scripts | `FileVersion`, `MergeItem`, `SourceConfig` dataclasses; `FileScanner`, `MergeEngine`, `EditorHistoryExtractor` class patterns | Referenced in `CLAUDE.md` documentation; `restore_deleted_files.ps1` reimplements editor history extraction logic |\\n\\n## Shared Types\\n- **`FileVersion` / `MergeItem` / `SourceConfig` dataclasses** — defined here, referenced in `CLAUDE.md` (project-root-and-scripts) and consumed by templates via template context variables.\\n- **Flask template context variables** — defined here (passed from route handlers), consumed by web-templates. Key variables: `stats`, `items`, `versions`, `hunks`, `filepath`, `coverage`, `sources`, `all_sessions`.\\n- **SSE event protocol** — defined here (event types: `done`, `progress`, `scanning`, `source_count`, `source_done`, `error`, `heartbeat`, etc.), consumed by web-templates via `EventSource` API.\\n- **EditorHistoryExtractor pattern** — defined here as a Python class, reimplemented in `restore_deleted_files.ps1` as standalone PowerShell functions.\\n\\n## Configuration\\n- **`app.secret_key`** — hardcoded as `'file-merger-recovery-tool-2026'` in `file_merger.py`.\\n- **`DEFAULT_IGNORE`** — default set of patterns skipped during scanning; overridable via `/setup` form.\\n- **`SESSIONS_DIR`** — derived from `os.path.dirname(os.path.abspath(__file__))` + `'sessions'`.\\n- **`EDITOR_HISTORY_PATHS`** — hardcoded list of 8 paths under `%APPDATA%` and `%USERPROFILE%` for Windsurf/VS Code/Cursor history detection.\\n- **Flask dev server** — runs on `localhost:5000` with `debug=True` and `threaded=True`.\\n\\n## Impact Notes\\n- **web-templates** would break entirely if any Flask route path, template variable name, or SSE event type changes. All 13 templates depend on specific route URLs and context variable names.\\n- **project-root-and-scripts**: `restore_deleted_files.ps1` duplicates editor history extraction logic — changes to `EditorHistoryExtractor` or `FileScanner._scan_editor_history_source()` should be synced manually.\\n- **`sessions/` directory structure** is a cross-area concern — changing the SQLite schema or session folder layout affects persistence for all sessions.\\n- The global `state` dict is not thread-safe for multi-process deployments (e.g., WSGI with multiple workers). Each process would get its own copy.\\n- The monolithic structure means any change to models, services, persistence, or routes requires editing the same 2861-line file.\\n\\n## Change History\\n> Initial documentation generated by Spark.\\n\",\"kwargs\":\"{}\"}"
